Analysis of United States Tornado Data¶

Kiyoshi Amano 5/11/2022

Introduction¶

The violently rotating column of air known as a tornado has the potential to wreak a devastating amount of damage. While many of the deadliest recorded tornadoes within the United States (US) occurred in the 19th and 20th centuries, and advances in tracking and infrastructure have made us less susceptible to tornadoes, the threat still lingers. A 2011 tornado in Joplin, Missouri is the seventh deadliest recorded US tornado, taking the lives of 158 people.

The media commonly uses the term "Tornado Alley" for the area in the central US where tornadoes most frequently occur. While it is loosely defined, it generally refers to parts of states including Texas, Oklahoma, Kansas, Nebraska, Iowa, South Dakota, Minnesota, Wisconsin, Illinois, Indiana, Missouri, Arkansas, North Dakota, Montana, and Ohio. While most people have heard of this term, most people have never heard of "Dixie Alley," which refers to an area in the southern US that is also especially vulnerable to tornadoes. Geographical analysis of tornadoes in recent years has suggested that the region where tornadoes tend to originate is shifting towards the southeast as climate conditions change.

In order to better understand tornado trends in the US over time, this tutorial analyzes US tornado data to compare the Tornado Alley, Dixie Alley, and outside regions to determine how susceptible each area is to the threat of tornadoes. This analysis aims to bring awareness to the damage caused by tornadoes in the southern US in order to change media perception of what areas are at risk for tornadoes and inform policy decisions about where improvements to infrastructure are needed to better protect people from tornadoes.

Data Collection¶

The data used in this analysis comes from the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration's Storm Prediction Center. The dataset can be found downloadable as a CSV file at the bottom of this page: https://www.spc.noaa.gov/wcm/. It includes data for all recorded US tornadoes from 1950 to 2020, with information regarding the time and date, area, severity, injuries and fatalaties, and property damage. For this analysis, the focus will be on the dates tornadoes occurred, the latitude and longitude at which they originated, the number of deaths, and the property damage in dollars. More information about what exactly is recorded can be found here: https://www.spc.noaa.gov/wcm/data/SPC_severe_database_description.pdf.

Data Processing¶

The data is already in a relatively clean format, so little processing is necessary to reach the desired state. In order to adjust the table to suit our needs, we will ensure that any tornadoes without recorded starting latitude and longitude data are removed as their locations cannot be clearly plotted, and columns unneeded for our data analysis will be removed to ensure that relevant parts can be viewed more clearly. In addition, kept columns will be renamed to be more easily understood.

In [63]:
# Ensuring tornadoes without starting recorded coordinates are removed from the dataset
tornadoes = tornadoes.dropna(how = "any", subset = ["slat", "slon"])

# Removing unneeded columns
tornadoes = tornadoes.drop(["om", "mo", "dy", "tz", "stf", "stn", "inj", "closs", "mag", "elat", "elon", "len", "wid", "ns", "sn", "sg", "f1", "f2", "f3", "f4", "fc"], axis = 1)

# Renaming columns
tornadoes.columns = ["Year", "Date", "Time", "State", "Fatalities", "Loss", "StartLat", "StartLon"]

# Displaying the first 10 rows of the updated dataframe

Observations¶

Increasing concentration of tornadoes is displayed by green areas that become warmer until becoming red for the areas where tornadoes are most concentrated. The map does show high concentration in the Tornado Alley region of the central US. However, dark red areas are also present throughout the Dixie Alley region of the southern US. The threat of tornadoes in this region may be just as severe as Tornado Alley, or at least distinctly more severe than the rest of the US outside of the Alleys.

Number of Tornadoes over Time¶

Tornadoes will be divided into Tornado Alley, Dixie Alley, and neither categories and the number of tornadoes each year will be plotted over time. A regression line is added to allow for clearer visualization of trends for tornado occurrences in each region.

Exploratory Data Analysis¶

Based off the graphs and calculated regression lines for tornadoes in each region, it's clear that there are regional differences in the number of tornadoes over time. The overall number of tornadoes in Tornado Alley and Dixie Alley states are much higher than the number of tornadoes in all states outside these areas. However, the slopes of the lines for Tornado Alley and Dixie Alley are very similar, being 6.32 and 6.12 respectively, differing much more than the slope for the linear regression of tornadoes outside. Numbers of tornadoes recorded may also be affected by improvements in ability to track and record tornadoes since data first started being collected in 1950 which may contribute to the positive slope of all lines. However, the number of tornadoes in Tornado Alley and Dixie Alley in particular are increasing at a much faster rate than outside these areas.

Hypothesis Testing for Regional Differences in Number of Tornadoes over Time¶

The null hypothesis to test validity of will be that the region does not affect the number of tornadoes. Using the statsmodels linear regression functionality, an interaction variable will be added to calculate linear regression for each region's tornado count over time and calculate associated p-values to be displayed.

In [67]:
# Since Arkansas, Missouri, and Texas overlap between Dixie Alley and Tornado Alley, in order to provide clear classification
# of each recorded tornado, only states exclusive to each region are included in the classifications for Dixie Alley and
# Tornado Alley.

# This function returns a string classification depending on the state associated with a region
def classify(row):
    if row["State"].startswith(("OK", "KS", "NE", "IA", "SD", "MN", "WI", "IL", "IN", "ND", "MT", "OH")):
        return "Tornado"
    elif row["State"].startswith(("LA", "MS", "TN", "AL", "GA", "KY", "SC", "NC")):
        return "Dixie"
    elif row["State"].startswith(("TX", "MO", "AR")):
        return "Both"
    return "Neither"

# Creating a new column for region, with the values depending on the classification function's output for each row
tornadoes["Region"] = tornadoes.apply(lambda row: classify(row), axis = 1)

# Creating dataframe with year, region, and total number of tornadoes
region_counts = tornadoes.groupby(["Region", "Year"]).size().to_frame().reset_index()
region_counts.columns = ["Region", "Year", "Count"]

# Displaying the first 10 rows of the dataframe
print(region_counts.head(10))

# Calculating linear regression function for each region
regression_model = ols(formula = "Count ~ Year * Region", data = region_counts).fit()
print(regression_model.summary())

# Calculating slope for each region based off output
slope_both = regression_model.params[4]
slope_dixie = slope_both + regression_model.params[5]
slope_tornado = slope_both + regression_model.params[7]
slope_neither = slope_both + regression_model.params[6]

# Printing slope for each region
print("Dixie Alley Slope: " + str(slope_dixie))
print("Tornado Alley Slope: " + str(slope_tornado))
print("Outside Region Slope: " + str(slope_neither))

Hypothesis Testing Results¶

As seen by the p-values of 0.000 displayed under the P>|t| column for linear regression coefficients, the calculated linear regressions for states exclusive in Dixie Alley and Tornado Alley are statistically significant. The null hypothesis can be rejected so the number of tornadoes is affected by the regions as classified here. In addition, the slopes for the regression lines for Dixie Alley and Tornado Alley differ by just 4.4843%, whereas they differ from regions outside both by 56.094% and 60.1997% respectively. The trends in increasing numbers of tornadoes for Dixie Alley and Tornado Alley are very similar.

Investigating Trends in Number of Deaths¶

While the overall number of tornadoes is highest in Tornado Alley, Dixie Alley may be more severely affected. According to Dr. Harold Brooks, the senior research scientist at the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration, southeastern states are the most vulnerable due to increased poverty conditions as well as lower level of infrastructure, with many living in manufactured homes. It's time to investigate how the number of deaths resulting from tornadoes differs in each region. The null hypothesis will be that region has no impact on the number of deaths caused by tornadoes.

Hypothesis Testing Results¶

As seen by the p-values that are greater than the significance value of 0.05 displayed under the P>|t| column for linear regression coefficients, the calculated linear regressions for states exclusive in Dixie Alley and Tornado Alley are not statistically significant. The null hypothesis cannot be rejected so the number of deaths is not affected by the regions as classified here. However, it's interesting to note the slopes calculated by the linear regression for states exclusive in Dixie Allie, Tornado Alley, and those in neither. The slope for the number of deaths in states exclusive to Dixie Alley is actually positive. This means that the negative slope found by the regression for the graphs (which included states in both Dixie Alley and Tornado Alley) was due to the inclusion of these states. When you look at Dixie Alley exclusive states, the number of deaths from tornadoes is actually not decreasing, unlike for Tornado Alley exclusive states and those outside.

Investigating Trends in Property Damage¶

Since Dixie Alley has relatively lower levels of infrastructure, it's important to see whether tornadoes there are causing more severe property damage than outside the region. The null hypothesis to investigate validity of will be that region has no impact on the property damage caused by tornadoes.

In [70]:
# Single value dollar amount estimates for tornadoes only started in 1996 for this dataset.
# However, from 1996 to 2015 these values are represented in millions of dollars, whereas from 
# 2016 to 2020 these values are represented by whole dollar numbers. In order to create a single column
# that has a unified format, dataframes are divided and a new column is calculated for both which is then combined.

# Creating dataframes for tornadoes with property damage recorded in millions of dollars
tornado_alley_first = tornado_alley[(tornado_alley["Year"] > 1995) & (tornado_alley["Year"] < 2016)]
dixie_alley_first = dixie_alley[(dixie_alley["Year"] > 1995) & (dixie_alley["Year"] < 2016)]
neither_first = neither[(neither["Year"] > 1995) & (neither["Year"] < 2016)]

# Creating dataframes for tornadoes with property damage recorded in whole dollar values
tornado_alley_second = tornado_alley[tornado_alley["Year"] > 2015]
dixie_alley_second = dixie_alley[dixie_alley["Year"] > 2015]
neither_second = neither[neither["Year"] > 2015]

# Creating new column for property damage with whole dollar values
tornado_alley_first["PropDmg"] = tornado_alley_first["Loss"] * 1000000
dixie_alley_first["PropDmg"] = dixie_alley_first["Loss"] * 1000000
neither_first["PropDmg"] = neither_first["Loss"] * 1000000

# Creating new column for property damage that reflects the whole dollar values already recorded
tornado_alley_second["PropDmg"] = tornado_alley_second["Loss"]
dixie_alley_second["PropDmg"] = dixie_alley_second["Loss"]
neither_second["PropDmg"] = neither_second["Loss"]

# Combining the two dataframes to create unified dataframe with property damage for each region
tornado_alley_damage = pd.concat([tornado_alley_first, tornado_alley_second])

Hypothesis Testing Results¶

As seen by the p-values that are greater than the significance value of 0.05 displayed under the P>|t| column for linear regression coefficients, the calculated linear regressions for states exclusive in Dixie Alley and Tornado Alley are not statistically significant. The null hypothesis cannot be rejected so the property damage amount is not affected by the regions as classified here. However, the amount of property damage over time in states exclusive to both Dixie Alley and Tornado Alley is increasing, whereas it is decreasing in states outside.

Conclusion¶

As seen by the statistical analysis performed, the number of tornadoes is affected in a significant manner depending on classified region, but number of deaths and property damage is not. However, the trends as found through linear regression for Dixie Alley and Tornado Alley are much more similar than between those states and states outside. It's important to consider Dixie Alley as a region that is relatively vulnerable to tornadoes, and it should be included when discussing Tornado Alley in the media. In addition, the fact that Dixie Alley exclusive states are actually facing an increase in deaths, while the number of deaths in those outside of these states are decreasing, is a worrying trend. It's likely that the poor infrastructure in this region is a major contributor to this trend, and people should be made aware of this fact in order to bring greater attention to the issue so that more funding and improvements are made to infrastructure in this region to better protect against the threat of tornadoes.
